# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voronoi-fortune
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] In geometry, a **centroidal Voronoi tessellation** (**CVT**) is a special type of Voronoi tessellation in which the generating point of each Voronoi cell is also its centroid (center of mass).
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] It can be viewed as an optimal partition corresponding to an optimal distribution of generators.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] A number of algorithms can be used to generate centroidal Voronoi tessellations, including Lloyd's algorithm for K-means clustering or Quasi-Newton methods like BFGS.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] In two dimensions, the basic cell for the optimal CVT is a regular hexagon as it is proven to be the most dense packing of circles in 2D Euclidean space.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] Its three dimensional equivalent is the rhombic dodecahedral honeycomb, derived from the most dense packing of spheres in 3D Euclidean space.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] Centroidal Voronoi tessellations are useful in data compression, optimal quadrature, optimal quantization, clustering, and optimal mesh generation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] A weighted centroidal Voronoi diagrams is a CVT in which each centroid is weighted according to a certain function.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] For example, a grayscale image can be used as a density function to weight the points of a CVT, as a way to create digital stippling.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] Many patterns seen in nature are closely approximated by a centroidal Voronoi tessellation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/centroidal-voronoi-tessellation] Examples of this include the Giant's Causeway, the cells of the cornea, and the breeding pits of the male tilapia.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] The algorithm maintains both a sweep line and a *beach line*, which both move through the plane as the algorithm progresses.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] The sweep line is a straight line, which we may by convention assume to be vertical and moving left to right across the plane.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] At any time during the algorithm, the input points left of the sweep line will have been incorporated into the Voronoi diagram, while the points right of the sweep line will not have been considered yet.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] For each point left of the sweep line, one can define a parabola of points equidistant from that point and from the sweep line; the beach line is the boundary of the union of these parabolas.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] As the sweep line progresses, the vertices of the beach line, at which two parabolas cross, trace out the edges of the Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] The beach line progresses by keeping each parabola base exactly halfway between the points initially swept over with the sweep line, and the new position of the sweep line.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] Mathematically, this means each parabola is formed by using the sweep line as the directrix and the input point as the focus.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] The algorithm maintains as data structures a binary search tree describing the combinatorial structure of the beach line, and a priority queue listing potential future events that could change the beach line structure.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] Each such event may be prioritized by the *x*-coordinate of the sweep line at the point the event occurs.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] The algorithm itself then consists of repeatedly removing the next event from the priority queue, finding the changes the event causes in the beach line, and updating the data structures.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] As there are O(*n*) events to process (each being associated with some feature of the Voronoi diagram) and O(log *n*) time to process an event (each consisting of a constant number of binary search tree and priority queue operations) the total time is O(*n* log *n*).
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] Pseudocode description of the algorithm.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] Weighted sites may be used to control the areas of the Voronoi cells when using Voronoi diagrams to construct treemaps.
[src:voronoi-fortune/fortune-s-algorithm] In an additively weighted Voronoi diagram, the bisector between sites is in general a hyperbola, in contrast to unweighted Voronoi diagrams and power diagrams of disks for which it is a straight line.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In electrical engineering and computer science, **Lloyd's algorithm**, also known as **Voronoi iteration** or relaxation, is an algorithm named after Stuart P.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd for finding evenly spaced sets of points in subsets of Euclidean spaces and partitions of these subsets into well-shaped and uniformly sized convex cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Like the closely related *k*-means clustering algorithm, it repeatedly finds the centroid of each set in the partition and then re-partitions the input according to which of these centroids is closest.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In this setting, the mean operation is an integral over a region of space, and the nearest centroid operation results in Voronoi diagrams.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Although the algorithm may be applied most directly to the Euclidean plane, similar algorithms may also be applied to higher-dimensional spaces or to spaces with other non-Euclidean metrics.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's algorithm can be used to construct close approximations to centroidal Voronoi tessellations of the input, which can be used for quantization, dithering, and stippling.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Other applications of Lloyd's algorithm include smoothing of triangle meshes in the finite element method.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] The Voronoi diagram of the current site positions (red) at each iteration is shown.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] The gray circles denote the centroids of the Voronoi cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In the last image, the sites are very near the centroids of the Voronoi cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] A centroidal Voronoi tessellation has been found.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] The algorithm was first proposed by Stuart P.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd of Bell Labs in 1957 as a technique for pulse-code modulation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's work became widely circulated but remained unpublished until 1982.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] A similar algorithm was developed independently by Joel Max and published in 1960, which is why the algorithm is sometimes referred as the Lloyd-Max algorithm.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's algorithm starts by an initial placement of some number *k* of point sites in the input domain.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In mesh-smoothing applications, these would be the vertices of the mesh to be smoothed; in other applications they may be placed at random or by intersecting a uniform triangular mesh of the appropriate size with the input domain.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Because Voronoi diagram construction algorithms can be highly non-trivial, especially for inputs of dimension higher than two, the steps of calculating this diagram and finding the exact centroids of its cells may be replaced by an approximation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] A common simplification is to employ a suitable discretization of space like a fine pixel-grid, e.g. the texture buffer in graphics hardware.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Cells are materialized as pixels, labeled with their corresponding site-ID.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] A cell's new center is approximated by averaging the positions of all pixels assigned with the same label.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Alternatively, Monte Carlo methods may be used, in which random sample points are generated according to some fixed underlying probability distribution, assigned to the closest site, and averaged to approximate the centroid for each site.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Although embedding in other spaces is also possible, this elaboration assumes Euclidean space using the *L2* norm and discusses the two most relevant scenarios, which are two, and respectively three dimensions.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Integration of a cell and computation of its centroid (center of mass) is now given as a weighted combination of its simplices' centroids (in the following called ${\textstyle \mathbf {c} _{i}}$ ).
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Each time a relaxation step is performed, the points are left in a slightly more even distribution: closely spaced points move farther apart, and widely spaced points move closer together.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In one dimension, this algorithm has been shown to converge to a centroidal Voronoi diagram, also named a centroidal Voronoi tessellation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In higher dimensions, some slightly weaker convergence results are known.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] The algorithm converges slowly or, due to limitations in numerical precision, may not converge.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Therefore, real-world applications of Lloyd's algorithm typically stop once the distribution is "good enough." One common termination criterion is to stop when the maximum distance moved by any site in an iteration falls below a preset threshold.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Convergence can be accelerated by over-relaxing the points, which is done by moving each point **ω** times the distance to the center of mass, typically using a value slightly less than 2 for **ω**.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's method was originally used for scalar quantization, but it is clear that the method extends for vector quantization as well.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] As such, it is extensively used in data compression techniques in information theory.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's method is used in computer graphics because the resulting distribution has blue noise characteristics (see also Colors of noise), meaning there are few low-frequency components that could be interpreted as artifacts.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] It is particularly well-suited to picking sample positions for dithering.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's algorithm is also used to generate dot drawings in the style of stippling.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In this application, the centroids can be weighted based on a reference image to produce stipple illustrations matching an input image.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In the finite element method, an input domain with a complex geometry is partitioned into elements with simpler shapes; for instance, two-dimensional domains (either subsets of the Euclidean plane or surfaces in three dimensions) are often partitioned into triangles.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] It is important for the convergence of the finite element methods that these elements be well shaped; in the case of triangles, often elements that are nearly equilateral triangles are preferred.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's algorithm can be used to smooth a mesh generated by some other algorithm, moving its vertices and changing the connection pattern among its elements in order to produce triangles that are more closely equilateral.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] These applications typically use a smaller number of iterations of Lloyd's algorithm, stopping it to convergence, in order to preserve other features of the mesh such as differences in element size in different parts of the mesh.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] However, Laplacian smoothing can be applied more generally to meshes with non-triangular elements.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Lloyd's algorithm is usually used in a Euclidean space.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] Alternative distances, and alternative central points than the centroid, may be used instead.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] For example, Hausner (2001) used a variant of the Manhattan metric (with locally varying orientations) to find a tiling of an image by approximately square tiles whose orientation aligns with features of an image, which he used to simulate the construction of tiled mosaics.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] In this application, despite varying the metric, Hausner continued to use centroids as the representative points of their Voronoi cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/lloyd-s-algorithm] However, for metrics that differ more significantly from Euclidean, it may be appropriate to choose the minimizer of average squared distance as the representative point, in place of the centroid.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] In computational geometry, a **power diagram**, also called a **Laguerre–Voronoi diagram**, **Dirichlet cell complex**, **radical Voronoi tesselation** or a **sectional Dirichlet tesselation**, is a partition of the Euclidean plane into polygonal cells defined from a set of circles.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The cell for a given circle *C* consists of all the points for which the power distance to *C* is smaller than the power distance to the other circles.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The power diagram is a form of generalized Voronoi diagram, and coincides with the Voronoi diagram of the circle centers in the case that all the circles have equal radii.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] If *C* is a circle and *P* is a point outside *C*, then the power of *P* with respect to *C* is the square of the length of a line segment from *P* to a point *T* of tangency with *C*.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Equivalently, if *P* has distance *d* from the center of the circle, and the circle has radius *r*, then (by the Pythagorean theorem) the power is *d*2 − *r*2.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The same formula *d*2 − *r*2 may be extended to all points in the plane, regardless of whether they are inside or outside of *C*: points on *C* have zero power, and points inside *C* have negative power.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The power diagram of a set of *n* circles *C**i* is a partition of the plane into *n* regions *R**i* (called cells), such that a point *P* belongs to *R**i* whenever circle *C**i* is the circle minimizing the power of *P*.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] In the case *n* = 2, the power diagram consists of two halfplanes, separated by a line called the radical axis or chordale of the two circles.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Along the radical axis, both circles have equal power.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] More generally, in any power diagram, each cell *R**i* is a convex polygon, the intersection of the halfspaces bounded by the radical axes of circle *C**i* with each other circle.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Triples of cells meet at vertices of the diagram, which are the radical centers of the three circles whose cells meet at the vertex.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The power diagram may be seen as a weighted form of the Voronoi diagram of a set of point sites, a partition of the plane into cells within which one of the sites is closer than all the other sites.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] In contrast, in the power diagram, we may view each circle center as a site, and each circle's squared radius as a weight that is subtracted from the squared Euclidean distance before comparing it to other squared distances.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] In the case that all the circle radii are equal, this subtraction makes no difference to the comparison, and the power diagram coincides with the Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] A planar power diagram may also be interpreted as a planar cross-section of an unweighted three-dimensional Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Like the Voronoi diagram, the power diagram may be generalized to Euclidean spaces of any dimension.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The power diagram of *n* spheres in *d* dimensions is combinatorially equivalent to the intersection of a set of *n* upward-facing halfspaces in *d* + 1 dimensions, and vice versa.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Two-dimensional power diagrams may be constructed by an algorithm that runs in time O(*n* log *n*).
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] More generally, because of the equivalence with higher-dimensional halfspace intersections, *d*-dimensional power diagrams (for *d* > 2) may be constructed by an algorithm that runs in time $O(n^{\lceil d/2\rceil })$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] The power diagram may be used as part of an efficient algorithm for computing the volume of a union of spheres.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Intersecting each sphere with its power diagram cell gives its contribution to the total union, from which the volume may be computed in time proportional to the complexity of the power diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Other applications of power diagrams include data structures for testing whether a point belongs to a union of disks, algorithms for constructing the boundary of a union of disks, and algorithms for finding the closest two balls in a set of balls.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] It is also used for solving the semi-discrete optimal transportation problem which in turn has numerous applications, such as early universe reconstruction or fluid dynamics.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Aurenhammer (1987) traces the definition of the power distance to the work of 19th-century mathematicians Edmond Laguerre and Georgy Voronoy.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Fejes Tóth (1977) defined power diagrams and used them to show that the boundary of a union of *n* circular disks can always be illuminated from at most 2*n* point light sources.
[src:voronoi-fortune/power-diagram] Power diagrams have appeared in the literature under other names including the "Laguerre–Voronoi diagram", "Dirichlet cell complex", "radical Voronoi tesselation" and "sectional Dirichlet tesselation".
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In mathematics, a **Voronoi diagram** is a partition of a plane into regions close to each of a given set of objects.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] It can be classified also as a tessellation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In the simplest case, these objects are just finitely many points in the plane (called seeds, sites, or generators).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For each seed there is a corresponding region, called a **Voronoi cell** comprising all points of the plane closer to that seed than to any other.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram of a set of points is dual to that set's Delaunay triangulation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram is named after mathematician Georgy Voronoy, and is also called a **Voronoi tessellation**, a **Voronoi decomposition**, a **Voronoi partition**, or a **Dirichlet tessellation** (after Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi cells are also known as **Thiessen polygons**, after Alfred H.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams have practical and theoretical applications in many fields, mainly in science and technology, but also in visual art.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In the simplest case, shown in the first picture, we are given a finite set of points $\{p_{1},\dots p_{n}\}$ in the Euclidean plane.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In this case, each point $p_{k}$ has a corresponding cell $R_{k}$ consisting of the points in the Euclidean plane for which $p_{k}$ is the nearest site: the distance to $p_{k}$ is less than or equal to the minimum distance to any other site $p_{j}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For one other site $p_{j}$ , the points that are closer to $p_{k}$ than to $p_{j}$ , or equally distant, form a closed half-space, whose boundary is the perpendicular bisector of line segment $p_{j}p_{k}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Cell $R_{k}$ is the intersection of all of these $n-1$ half-spaces, and hence it is a convex polygon.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] When two cells in the Voronoi diagram share a boundary, it is a line segment, ray, or line, consisting of all the points in the plane that are equidistant to their two nearest sites.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The vertices of the diagram, where three or more of these boundaries meet, are the points that have three or more equally distant nearest sites.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle X}$ be a metric space with distance function ${\textstyle d}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle K}$ be a set of indices and let ${\textstyle (P_{k})_{k\in K}}$ be a tuple (indexed collection) of nonempty subsets (the sites) in the space ${\textstyle X}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram is simply the tuple of cells ${\textstyle (R_{k})_{k\in K}}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In principle, some of the sites can intersect and even coincide (an application is described below for sites representing shops), but usually they are assumed to be disjoint.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In addition, infinitely many sites are allowed in the definition (this setting has applications in geometry of numbers and crystallography), but again, in many cases only finitely many sites are considered.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Sometimes the induced combinatorial structure is referred to as the Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In general however, the Voronoi cells may not be convex or even connected.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In the usual Euclidean space, we can rewrite the formal definition in usual terms.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Each Voronoi polygon ${\textstyle R_{k}}$ is associated with a generator point ${\textstyle P_{k}}$ .
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle X}$ be the set of all points in the Euclidean space.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Let ${\textstyle P_{1}}$ be a point that generates its Voronoi region ${\textstyle R_{1}}$ , ${\textstyle P_{2}}$ that generates ${\textstyle R_{2}}$ , and ${\textstyle P_{3}}$ that generates ${\textstyle R_{3}}$ , and so on.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Then, as expressed by Tran *et al*, "all locations in the Voronoi polygon are closer to the generator point of that polygon than any other generator point in the Voronoi diagram in Euclidean plane".
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] As a simple illustration, consider a group of shops in a city.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Suppose we want to estimate the number of customers of a given shop.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] With all else being equal (price, products, quality of service, etc.), it is reasonable to assume that customers choose their preferred shop simply by distance considerations: they will go to the shop located nearest to them.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In this case the Voronoi cell $R_{k}$ of a given shop $P_{k}$ can be used for giving a rough estimate on the number of potential customers going to this shop (which is modeled by a point in our city).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The corresponding Voronoi diagrams look different for different distance metrics.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Informal use of Voronoi diagrams can be traced back to Descartes in 1644.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Peter Gustav Lejeune Dirichlet used two-dimensional and three-dimensional Voronoi diagrams in his study of quadratic forms in 1850.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] British physician John Snow used a Voronoi-like diagram in 1854 to illustrate how the majority of people who died in the Broad Street cholera outbreak lived closer to the infected Broad Street pump than to any other water pump.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams are named after Georgy Feodosievych Voronoy who defined and studied the general *n*-dimensional case in 1908.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams that are used in geophysics and meteorology to analyse spatially distributed data are called Thiessen polygons after American meteorologist Alfred H.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Thiessen, who used them to estimate rainfall from scattered measurements in 1911.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Other equivalent names for this concept (or particular important cases of it): Voronoi polyhedra, Voronoi polygons, domain(s) of influence, Voronoi decomposition, Voronoi tessellation(s), Dirichlet tessellation(s).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi tessellations of regular lattices of points in two or three dimensions give rise to many familiar tessellations.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The corresponding cells are known as Wigner–Seitz cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For the set of points (*x*, *y*) with *x* in a discrete set *X* and *y* in a discrete set *Y*, we get rectangular tiles with the points not necessarily at their centers.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Although a normal Voronoi cell is defined as the set of points closest to a single point in *S*, an *n*th-order Voronoi cell is defined as the set of points having a particular set of *n* points in *S* as its *n* nearest neighbors.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Higher-order Voronoi diagrams also subdivide space.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Higher-order Voronoi diagrams can be generated recursively.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] To generate the *n*th-order Voronoi diagram from set *S*, start with the (*n* − 1)th-order diagram and replace each cell generated by *X* = {*x*1, *x*2, ..., *x**n*−1} with a Voronoi diagram generated on the set *S* − *X*.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For a set of *n* points, the (*n* − 1)th-order Voronoi diagram is called a farthest-point Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For a given set of points *P* = {*p*1, *p*2, ..., *p**n*}, the farthest-point Voronoi diagram divides the plane into cells in which the same point of *P* is the farthest point.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] A point of *P* has a cell in the farthest-point Voronoi diagram if and only if it is a vertex of the convex hull of *P*.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The boundaries of the cells in the farthest-point Voronoi diagram have the structure of a topological tree, with infinite rays as its leaves.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Every finite tree is isomorphic to the tree formed in this way from a farthest-point Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] As implied by the definition, Voronoi cells can be defined for metrics other than Euclidean, such as the Mahalanobis distance or Manhattan distance.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] However, in these cases the boundaries of the Voronoi cells may be more complicated than in the Euclidean case, since the equidistant locus for two points may fail to be subspace of codimension 1, even in the two-dimensional case.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] A weighted Voronoi diagram is the one in which the function of a pair of points to define a Voronoi cell is a distance function modified by multiplicative or additive weights assigned to generator points.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] In contrast to the case of Voronoi cells defined using a distance which is a metric, in this case some of the Voronoi cells may be empty.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] A power diagram is a type of Voronoi diagram defined from a set of circles using the power distance; it can also be thought of as a weighted Voronoi diagram in which a weight defined from the radius of each circle is added to the squared Euclidean distance from the circle's center.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi diagram of n points in d -dimensional space can have ${\textstyle O(n^{\lceil d/2\rceil })}$ vertices, requiring the same bound for the amount of memory needed to store an explicit description of it.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Therefore, Voronoi diagrams are often not feasible for moderate or high dimensions.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] A more space-efficient alternative is to use approximate Voronoi diagrams.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi diagrams are also related to other geometric structures such as the medial axis (which has found applications in image segmentation, optical character recognition, and other computational applications), straight skeleton, and zone diagrams.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] It is used in meteorology and engineering hydrology to find the weights for precipitation data of stations over an area (watershed).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The points generating the polygons are the various station that record precipitation data.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Perpendicular bisectors are drawn to the line joining any two stations.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] This results in the formation of polygons around the stations.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] The area $(A_{i})$ touching station point is known as influence area of the station.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Several efficient algorithms are known for constructing Voronoi diagrams, either directly (as the diagram itself) or indirectly by starting with a Delaunay triangulation and then obtaining its dual.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Direct algorithms include Fortune's algorithm, an O(*n* log(*n*)) algorithm for generating a Voronoi diagram from a set of points in a plane.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Bowyer–Watson algorithm, an O(*n* log(*n*)) to O(*n*2) algorithm for generating a Delaunay triangulation in any number of dimensions, can be used in an indirect algorithm for the Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] For discrete grid approximations (such as pixel rendering), the Jump Flooding Algorithm (JFA) and its variants are widely used on commodity graphics hardware (GPUs).
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Originally introduced by Rong Guodong in 2006, the standard JFA computes an approximate Voronoi diagram in $O(\log N)$ parallel passes over an $N\times N$ grid.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Subsequent optimizations, such as the 2019 randomized JFA-star variant introduced by Maciej A.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Czyzewski, shift the pass complexity from scaling with grid resolution to the total number of seed points ( n ), achieving faster convergence in roughly $O(\log ^{*}n)$ passes.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Lloyd's algorithm and its generalization via the Linde–Buzo–Gray algorithm (aka k-means clustering) use the construction of Voronoi diagrams as a subroutine.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] These methods alternate between steps in which one constructs the Voronoi diagram for a set of seed points, and steps in which the seed points are moved to new locations that are more central within their cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] These methods can be used in spaces of arbitrary dimension to iteratively converge towards a specialized form of the Voronoi diagram, called a Centroidal Voronoi tessellation, where the sites have been moved to points that are also the geometric centers of their cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/voronoi-diagram] Voronoi meshes can also be generated in 3D.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In mathematics, a **weighted Voronoi diagram** in *n* dimensions is a generalization of a Voronoi diagram.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] The Voronoi cells in a weighted Voronoi diagram are defined in terms of a distance function.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] The distance function may specify the usual Euclidean distance, or may be some other, special distance function.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In weighted Voronoi diagrams, each site has a weight that influences the distance computation.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] The idea is that larger weights indicate more important sites, and such sites will get bigger Voronoi cells.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In a **multiplicatively weighted Voronoi diagram**, the distance between a point and a site is divided by the (positive) weight of the site.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In the plane under the ordinary Euclidean distance, the multiplicatively weighted Voronoi diagram is also called **circular Dirichlet tessellation** and its edges are circular arcs and straight line segments.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] A Voronoi cell may be non-convex, disconnected and may have holes.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] This diagram arises, e.g., as a model of crystal growth, where crystals from different points may grow with different speed.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] Since crystals may grow in empty space only and are continuous objects, a natural variation is the **crystal Voronoi diagram**, in which the cells are defined somewhat differently.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In an **additively weighted Voronoi diagram**, weights are subtracted from the distances.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] In the plane under the ordinary Euclidean distance this diagram is also known as the **hyperbolic Dirichlet tessellation** and its edges are arcs of hyperbolas and straight line segments.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] The power diagram is defined when weights are subtracted from the squared Euclidean distance.
[src:voronoi-fortune/weighted-voronoi-diagram] It can also be defined using the power distance defined from a set of circles.
